description: Mushroom found growing in mown grass about 10 ft from woods edge.  No others found.  NE Kansas, Wyandotte County.  7:30 am CDT 5/17/18.  No picture in situ, photos taken at home.  Photo shows specimen after breaking apart in transport.   About 12"Lx8"Wx9"H.  Weight 4.5 lbs before cutting away woody base and parts with grass & duff encased.  Emerged from soil with no wood visible on surface.  Mature White Oak is about 12 ft away so the mushroom may be utilizing its root system.  The grass had been mowed to a height of 3" two days previously.  I have found other members of this genus before, but never one as fresh and fleshy as this one.  Delicious, too!

The iPhone app gave L. cincinnatus as the first choice, but since I had never heard of it, I opted for the 2nd choice L. sulphureus, a name with which I as familiar.  We remarked that this was not at all YELLOW, but assumed it was just very fresh. Unfortuately the green you see is Poison Ivy.   The split apparently occurred with a 1997 paper.  The identifying features are provided in a paper by Volk
https://botit.botany.wisc.edu/toms_fungi/jul2001.html
There were 3 clones, two as rosettes growing up out of roots and one on the trunk.  These are also characteristic of Cincinnatus. The host was a half-dead Scarlet Oak

Almost white caps and pale pored, with a faint peach overtone, but growing on an old hardwood stump, not arising from roots like L. cincinnatus usually does. This is the fourth time I have found this during this summer, once on a branch as small as 2" across. The almost white cap and creamy pore surface with a peachy tint has been consistent with all observations, and all have been above ground on dead wood.

This specimen is on an old stump, the photo with the camera case shows size, the case is 5" long.  As a side note, the mushroom cooked up to a soft orange shade, surprising since the cap was so pale. (Last two photos).

Another report on the related L. sulphureus:

As such, many field guides[who?] request that those who eat Laetiporus exercise caution by only eating fresh, young brackets and begin with small quantities to see how well it sits in their stomach.

description: Updated pictures with growth after 2 days.

As of 6/5/23 I am not entirely sure of what species of fungus this is. I am under the impression that it is white-pored chicken of the woods but I have never encountered one of these while foraging before. Confirmation or suggestions as to what this may be would be greatly appreciated. 

Large, fruiting body. Right next to a deciduous tree stump, but not growing from it or connected to it in anyway. The outside is pale orange and has a soft, smooth texture. The top of it is paler and feels harder, almost rubbery. The inside flesh is the color of raw salmon and feels incredibly wet. The flesh was very tender to cut into, I didn’t have a foraging knife on me and had to use my keys (it worked well.) The flesh itself was stringy with the flesh deeper inside of the fruiting body being pale, almost white. When squeezed the flesh released a clear liquid.
